LINE.Text: Growth plate injuries in children and teens
Ever wonder how bones grow and children get taller? The key is the growth plate. This
smooth, elastic cartilage is found near each end of a growing child's long bones, such as
those found in the shoulder, elbow, wrist, hand, hip, knee, ankle and foot. Bone growth
occurs at the growth plates. Once a child stops growing, the growth plates close to

Boys are twice as likely as girls to injure a
growth plate, since their growth plates stay
open longer than those of girls. Boys generally
stop growing between ages 16 and 18. and
girls finish their growth between 14 and 16.
Growth plate injuries may result from an accident, such as a fall, or from overuse
(stress from a repeated activity). 1 in 3 of these injuries occurs during competitive
sports, while 1 in 5 occurs during recreational activities.
